(Internet-Draft           FedFS Security Addendum               July 2013) s
5 635 M
(1.  Introduction) s
5 613 M
(   Requirements for federated filesystems are described in [RFC5716].) s
5 602 M
(   Specification of the protocol used by administrators to configure) s
5 591 M
(   fileservers and construct namespaces is provided in [FEDFS-ADMIN].) s
5 580 M
(   Specification of the protocol allowing fileservers to store namespace) s
5 569 M
(   information is provided in [FEDFS-NSDB].) s
5 547 M
(   These documents are now immutable.  However, some security-related) s
5 536 M
(   concerns have arisen that should be addressed immediately rather than) s
5 525 M
(   waiting for another version of these protocols to be ratified.) s
5 503 M
(1.1.  Problem Statement: GSSAPI service name for ADMIN) s
5 481 M
(   After IESG review, the Security Considerations chapter of) s
5 470 M
(   [FEDFS-ADMIN] now specifically requires that implementations of this) s
5 459 M
(   protocol support GSSAPI security mechanisms.) s
5 437 M
(   ADMIN protocol clients must use a service principal to establish a) s
5 426 M
(   GSS context shared with an ADMIN server.  To construct the service) s
5 415 M
(   principal, clients need to know a priori the protocol's GSSAPI) s
5 404 M
(   service name.  The form of that service name is described in chapter) s
5 393 M
(   4 of [RFC2724].) s
5 371 M
(   According to [RFC2743], requesting an addition to the "GSSAPI/) s
5 360 M
(   Kerberos/SASL Service Names" registry requires a specification.) s
5 349 M
(   Because [FEDFS-ADMIN] cannot be changed, a new specification must be) s
5 338 M
(   provided.) s
5 316 M
(1.2.  Problem Statement: Compromised NSDBs) s
5 294 M
(   The FedFS ADMIN RPC protocol provides a mechanism for provisioning) s
5 283 M
(   NSDBs on remote fileservers.  The operations it provides are) s
5 272 M
(   FEDFS_SET_NSDB_PARAMS, FEDFS_GET_NSDB_PARAMS, and) s
5 261 M
(   FEDFS_GET_LIMITED_NSDB_PARAMS.) s
5 239 M
(   FEDFS_SET_NSDB_PARAMS specifies the name of an NSDB and the security) s
5 228 M
(   mode to use when connecting to this NSDB.  The fileserver connects to) s
5 217 M
(   an NSDB in order to resolve a FedFS junction.  The ADMIN protocol) s
5 206 M
(   specification further says:) s
5 184 M
(      On success, this operation returns FEDFS_OK.  When the operation) s
5 173 M
(      returns, the new connection parameters SHOULD be used for all) s
5 162 M
(      subsequent LDAP connections to the given NSDB.  Existing) s
5 151 M
(      connections MAY be terminated and re-established using the new) s
5 140 M
(      connection parameters.  The connection parameters SHOULD be) s
5 129 M
(      durable across fileserver reboots.) s
5 74 M
(Lever                   Expires January 11, 2014                [Page 4]) s
