(Internet-Draft           FedFS Security Addendum               July 2013) s
5 635 M
(   There are two security modes defined in the protocol specification:) s
5 624 M
(   FEDFS_SEC_NONE, which does not authenticate the LDAP server; and) s
5 613 M
(   FEDFS_SEC_TLS, which uses START_TLS \(RFC 4513\) to authenticate the) s
5 602 M
(   LDAP server.) s
5 580 M
(   When FEDFS_SEC_TLS is specified with the FEDFS_SET_NSDB_PARAMS) s
5 569 M
(   operation, an x.509v3 certificate chain is also provided to the) s
5 558 M
(   fileserver.  The fileserver uses the provided certificate to) s
5 547 M
(   authenticate subsequent connections to this NSDB.  The) s
5 536 M
(   FEDFS_SET_NSDB_PARAMS operation can change the connection security) s
5 525 M
(   used by a fileserver to connect to a particular NSDB from NONE to TLS) s
5 514 M
(   or TLS to NONE.) s
5 492 M
(   Over time, domain administrators add NSDB connection parameters to) s
5 481 M
(   each of their fileservers to enable FedFS junction resolution.  The) s
5 470 M
(   specified NSDB may be the domain's own, or it might be an NSDB in a) s
5 459 M
(   foreign domain.) s
5 437 M
(   Many junctions on multiple fileservers can be created that use a) s
5 426 M
(   particular NSDB.  There is no way to find such junctions without an) s
5 415 M
(   exhaustive search.  Since filesystem namespace topology can evolve) s
5 404 M
(   arbitrarily over time, a recorded pathname of any junction is almost) s
5 393 M
(   guaranteed to become stale.) s
5 371 M
(   Now suppose we have two FedFS domains: example.net and) s
5 360 M
(   university.edu.  Suppose university.edu fileservers have a number of) s
5 349 M
(   junctions that refer to locations maintained by example.net, and thus) s
5 338 M
(   university.net's fileservers are configured to resolve junctions on) s
5 327 M
(   example.net's NSDB.) s
5 305 M
(   One day Mallory compromises example.net's NSDB, but the domain) s
5 294 M
(   administrator there is on a long vacation.  The administrator at) s
5 283 M
(   university.net discovers the compromise immediately, but has no) s
5 272 M
(   control over the foreign NSDB and cannot create a fresh x.509) s
5 261 M
(   certificate or verify that the contents of the NSDB are unmolested.) s
5 250 M
(   The only choice is to find and remove every junction in the) s
5 239 M
(   university.edu domain that contains the compromised NSDB.) s
5 217 M
(   If university.edu is using a good implementation of FedFS, the) s
5 206 M
(   administrative tools it provides might allow an administrator to) s
5 195 M
(   simply visit each of its fileservers and mark the example.net NSDB as) s
5 184 M
(   compromised.  Any junction resolution that attempts to use that NSDB) s
5 173 M
(   would fail, but all junctions remain in place.  When example.net's) s
5 162 M
(   administrator gets back from holiday and cleans up the mess, the) s
5 151 M
(   university.edu administrator can then update each of her fileservers) s
5 140 M
(   with fresh connection parameters for that NSDB.) s
5 118 M
(   However, none of this can be done remotely using the FedFS ADMIN) s
5 74 M
(Lever                   Expires January 11, 2014                [Page 5]) s
