(3.  Fencing Compromised NSDBs) s
5 613 M
(   An NSDB is considered "foreign" relative to a particular FedFS domain) s
5 602 M
(   if that domain's administrator has no administrative access to that) s
5 591 M
(   NSDB.) s
5 569 M
(   When a FedFS domain administrator is faced with a foreign NSDB that) s
5 558 M
(   is compromised or otherwise unusable, and in the absense of an) s
5 547 M
(   implementation-provided mechanism for fencing an NSDB, the) s
5 536 M
(   administrator can fence that NSDB using the following technique.) s
5 514 M
(   1.  The administrator locally generates a new certificate for the) s
5 503 M
(       compromised foreign NSDB.  The certificate can be self-signed, or) s
5 492 M
(       signed by the administrator's local certificate authority.) s
5 470 M
(   2.  The administrator distributes this certificate to all of her) s
5 459 M
(       domain's fileservers using the FedFS ADMIN protocol or some other) s
5 448 M
(       secure means.  The connection security for the foreign NSDB is) s
5 437 M
(       set to FEDFS_SEC_TLS on each of the local domain's fileservers.) s
5 415 M
(   3.  The administrator requests fresh certificate material from the) s
5 404 M
(       administrator of the foreign NSDB.) s
5 382 M
(   4.  When the threat has passed and the foreign NSDB is safe to use) s
5 371 M
(       again, the administrator can distribute the new valid certificate) s
5 360 M
(       material to her domain's fileservers.) s
5 338 M
(   Step 2 guarantees that, within the administrator's local FedFS) s
5 327 M
(   domain, resolving a junction that references the compromised foreign) s
5 316 M
(   NSDB will fail until the updated certificate material is available.) s
5 74 M
